author: @vishalk8905
text: Normalization is good to use when you know that the distribution of your data does not follow a Gaussian distribution.  Standardization, on the other hand, can be helpful in cases where the data follows a Gaussian distribution. However, this does not have to be necessarily true. Also, unlike normalization, standardization does not have a bounding range. So, even if you have outliers in your data, they will not be affected by standardization.
